WEBVTT

00:02.769 --> 00:05.772
[jazz music]

00:05.804 --> 00:12.846
♪ ♪

00:18.417 --> 00:20.152
[cheers and applause]

00:20.185 --> 00:22.288
- From the Penn &
Teller Theater

00:22.321 --> 00:24.423
at the Rio Hotel in Las Vegas,

00:24.457 --> 00:28.827
here's our host,
Alyson Hannigan.

00:28.861 --> 00:35.902
♪ ♪

00:40.506 --> 00:42.575
- Welcome to "Fool Us,"
where we showcase

00:42.609 --> 00:44.710
the world's best magicians.

00:44.743 --> 00:47.347
We've had acts from Germany,
Argentina,

00:47.380 --> 00:49.048
Australia, India, China,

00:49.082 --> 00:52.618
and even as far away as Reno.
[laughter]

00:52.652 --> 00:55.722
We're just like the Olympics,
but without the four-year wait.

00:55.755 --> 00:58.390
So let the games began
as we bring out

00:58.424 --> 01:02.728
our gold medalists of magic,
Penn and Teller.

01:02.762 --> 01:05.731
[cheers and applause]

01:05.765 --> 01:12.805
♪ ♪

01:16.709 --> 01:19.212
Don't forget
every magician who manages

01:19.245 --> 01:22.215
to stump Penn and Teller
wins a "Fool Us" trophy

01:22.248 --> 01:25.518
and a spot
in the Las Vegas spectacular.

01:25.551 --> 01:28.521
And here's tonight's
first potential Fooler.

01:30.722 --> 01:33.926
- Magic is my second career.
I was a graphic artist first,

01:33.960 --> 01:36.628
which is also about
creating other realities.

01:36.662 --> 01:38.897
In those days,
magic was my hobby.

01:38.932 --> 01:41.100
Then I got an internship
on a TV show

01:41.134 --> 01:44.871
and I became fascinated
by how cameras and editing

01:44.903 --> 01:47.006
can build a world.

01:47.039 --> 01:49.575
So I went back to school
to study filmmaking.

01:49.609 --> 01:53.646
It was very expensive, so
I supported myself with magic,

01:53.680 --> 01:55.215
and a funny thing happened.

01:55.247 --> 01:56.983
My magic got bigger
and bigger.

01:57.015 --> 01:59.352
Personal appearances
became stage shows.

01:59.384 --> 02:02.489
I realized I could combine
everything in a theater:

02:02.522 --> 02:06.459
graphics, cinema,
storytelling, and magic.

02:06.492 --> 02:09.262
And when I put
all these things together,

02:09.294 --> 02:12.164
I finally knew
what I wanted to be.

02:12.198 --> 02:15.168
I love being a magician
because I can build my life

02:15.200 --> 02:19.372
around play.
You never have to grow up.

02:19.405 --> 02:21.774
As a kid, I would put on shows
in my backyard

02:21.807 --> 02:24.009
and charge
the neighborhood kids a fee.

02:24.043 --> 02:26.746
My dad passed away
when I was 17,

02:26.778 --> 02:29.449
so all he ever saw was
my backyard magic.

02:29.481 --> 02:31.484
When I perform,
like I will tonight,

02:31.518 --> 02:34.120
using skills
dad never got to see,

02:34.153 --> 02:36.489
I like to imagine
he's watching me.

02:36.522 --> 02:38.691
Who knows?
Maybe he is.

02:39.759 --> 02:42.795
[cheers and applause]

02:44.463 --> 02:46.064
- All the way from Germany,

02:46.098 --> 02:48.968
say, "bitte willkommen"
to Mellow.

02:49.002 --> 02:52.038
[cheers and applause]

02:53.872 --> 02:56.408
- Hi, Penn.
Hello, Teller.

02:56.442 --> 02:58.811
Magicians are often accused
of using camera tricks

02:58.844 --> 03:00.947
to make their magic happen.

03:00.979 --> 03:03.550
Well, I admit.

03:03.582 --> 03:06.451
What you are about to see
is a camera trick

03:06.485 --> 03:09.556
because it is a trick...

03:09.588 --> 03:12.091
with a camera.
[audience murmurs]

03:12.125 --> 03:13.592
Outside of the magical world,

03:13.626 --> 03:17.229
there's nothing that comes
as close to magic as Polaroids.

03:17.263 --> 03:19.932
You press the shutter button...

03:19.966 --> 03:22.502
[soft upbeat music]

03:22.534 --> 03:25.305
And a complete blank picture
pops out.

03:25.337 --> 03:28.007
Then if you wait a minute,
the image appears.

03:28.040 --> 03:30.143
Before the smartphone,
this is how memories

03:30.175 --> 03:32.412
were captured instantly.

03:32.444 --> 03:33.812
For example...

03:33.846 --> 03:35.882
♪ ♪

03:35.914 --> 03:39.519
[chuckles]
This one.

03:39.551 --> 03:42.588
This is me as a kid
sitting in the bathtub

03:42.622 --> 03:44.723
with a lot of bubbles.

03:44.757 --> 03:48.860
Okay. Way too much bubbles.
Give me a second.

03:48.895 --> 03:50.329
[audience exclaims]

03:50.362 --> 03:53.399
[applause]

03:54.334 --> 03:56.235
I've got lots
of these pictures.

03:56.269 --> 03:59.739
like this one.
[chuckles]

03:59.771 --> 04:01.241
My money shot.
[laughter]

04:01.274 --> 04:02.474
If I ever needed,

04:02.508 --> 04:06.812
I can get cash back
at any time, even now.

04:06.846 --> 04:09.348
[applause]

04:09.382 --> 04:13.019
♪ ♪

04:13.051 --> 04:17.055
[chuckles] And these are
my parents' wedding photos.

04:17.089 --> 04:19.959
I know it sounds crazy,
but I couldn't find a photo

04:19.992 --> 04:23.362
with both of them together
in one picture.

04:23.396 --> 04:25.197
Maybe we can fix that.

04:25.230 --> 04:32.271
♪ ♪

04:33.372 --> 04:35.675
[audience exclaims]

04:35.707 --> 04:37.377
I brought some
more pictures with me

04:37.409 --> 04:40.045
and I want to share them
with this volunteer.

04:40.079 --> 04:43.048
Please, come on stage.

04:43.081 --> 04:46.119
Hi. Please take a seat.
What's your name?

04:46.151 --> 04:47.452
- Magam.
- Magam.

04:47.487 --> 04:49.622
And we've said nothing
up in advance, right?

04:49.656 --> 04:51.257
- Correct.
- Okay.

04:51.290 --> 04:55.827
Please reach into the basket
and mix up the pictures.

04:55.862 --> 04:57.430
Look through
all these photographs

04:57.463 --> 05:00.600
and you'll see, they're all
different moments, right?

05:00.632 --> 05:03.336
- Mm-hmm.
- Okay. Please select a photo

05:03.369 --> 05:05.605
that is facedown
and hold it against your chest

05:05.637 --> 05:08.841
so I can't see which moment
of my life you chose.

05:08.875 --> 05:13.045
♪ ♪

05:13.079 --> 05:14.379
- Okay.
- Okay.

05:14.413 --> 05:16.249
Secretly,
for the very first time,

05:16.281 --> 05:18.151
take a look at the picture

05:18.184 --> 05:21.954
and try to remember
everything in detail.

05:21.987 --> 05:23.156
- Mm-hmm.

05:23.189 --> 05:26.326
- Then hold it close
to your body again.

05:26.358 --> 05:30.163
Magam, imagine an invisible,
big, blank photo

05:30.196 --> 05:31.697
right in front of us.

05:31.730 --> 05:34.067
Try to project the picture
you have in your mind

05:34.100 --> 05:36.168
clearly onto the blank photo

05:36.201 --> 05:40.005
and let's see if I take
a real photo of it.

05:40.038 --> 05:47.012
♪ ♪

05:47.045 --> 05:50.350
Here's the picture that just
came out of my magical camera.

05:50.382 --> 05:53.151
I'll hold it out here
while it develops.

05:53.185 --> 05:57.023
So out of that basket
of tons of different photos,

05:57.055 --> 06:01.060
would you please show us which
photo you randomly selected?

06:01.093 --> 06:03.428
♪ ♪

06:03.463 --> 06:04.663
[chuckles]

06:04.697 --> 06:08.701
My first day of school.
Very great memory.

06:08.735 --> 06:12.271
I think we had enough time
for the new picture to develop

06:12.305 --> 06:14.005
and amazingly,

06:14.040 --> 06:16.442
it is the exact same picture
you chose.

06:16.475 --> 06:19.345
[audience exclaims]

06:19.379 --> 06:21.346
[applause]

06:21.380 --> 06:23.815
This is the magic of Polaroids.

06:23.850 --> 06:26.218
Every time you take a look
at the picture like this,

06:26.252 --> 06:28.454
it's like having a glimpse
of the feeling you had

06:28.487 --> 06:30.723
right in the moment
when it was taken.

06:30.757 --> 06:33.425
Definitely, no camera tricks
are needed for this.

06:33.459 --> 06:37.062
Just a lot of imagination
and a little bit of magic.

06:37.096 --> 06:39.699
♪ ♪

06:39.731 --> 06:42.268
[audience exclaims]

06:42.300 --> 06:43.269
♪ ♪

06:43.302 --> 06:46.338
[cheers and applause]

06:48.274 --> 06:50.543
- Whoa.

06:50.576 --> 06:53.612
[applause]

06:55.415 --> 06:56.882
Hi.

06:56.915 --> 06:59.252
Why do they call you Mellow?

06:59.284 --> 07:02.588
- Um, I think it describes
my personality

07:02.622 --> 07:04.023
and my style of magic.

07:04.055 --> 07:07.360
- Cool. So you started
magic very young?

07:07.392 --> 07:10.163
- Yeah. I started magic
at a very young age.

07:10.196 --> 07:13.298
Before this, I was in a circus
school and learned juggling.

07:13.331 --> 07:16.035
And later, I find out
that magic is another way

07:16.067 --> 07:20.773
to impress and amaze people
with also physical movements.

07:20.807 --> 07:22.240
- Oh, cool.

07:22.274 --> 07:25.076
What kind of obstacles did you
face when you got started?

07:25.110 --> 07:28.880
- I was a very shy person
as a kid,

07:28.915 --> 07:30.382
so it was very hard for me

07:30.415 --> 07:32.451
to perform
in front of other people,

07:32.485 --> 07:35.454
but magic helped me
to express myself

07:35.487 --> 07:38.156
and make me more confident.

07:38.191 --> 07:41.127
- How is the magic community
in Germany?

07:41.159 --> 07:44.197
- The magic community
is very, very great,

07:44.230 --> 07:47.834
but the audience is
a very hard one. [chuckles]

07:47.867 --> 07:49.034
- Oh.
Why?

07:49.067 --> 07:50.836
- They are less enthusiastic

07:50.870 --> 07:54.240
and it's, well, very difficult
to get emotions

07:54.273 --> 07:57.242
and visible reactions
from the German audience.

07:57.276 --> 07:58.845
- So you don't really
actually know

07:58.877 --> 08:01.279
if a German audience
likes your magic or not?

08:01.314 --> 08:02.682
- Yeah, yeah.

08:02.714 --> 08:06.552
They sit and watch the act
and nice applause.

08:06.586 --> 08:09.288
And after the show,
they came to you and say,

08:09.322 --> 08:12.725
"The best I ever seen."
[laughter]

08:12.757 --> 08:14.259
- Okay.

08:14.293 --> 08:17.497
Let's see if the memory you
made tonight includes a trophy.

08:18.497 --> 08:20.600
- Hey, Mellow.
Boy, what a nice routine.

08:20.632 --> 08:22.401
Really good. You know...

08:22.435 --> 08:23.870
- Thank you.

08:23.903 --> 08:29.141
- Polaroid cameras, instant
cameras were so magical,

08:29.175 --> 08:31.476
you know, in a strange way,

08:31.511 --> 08:34.346
so much more magical
than our smartphones

08:34.379 --> 08:35.615
we all carry around.

08:35.648 --> 08:37.350
Just that thing being spit out

08:37.383 --> 08:40.052
and developing in front of us
was just so beautiful.

08:40.086 --> 08:44.690
And you've taken that and used
it like a witch's spell.

08:44.724 --> 08:46.658
You've taken something
out of the past

08:46.692 --> 08:49.061
and really gotten
all the magic out of it.

08:49.095 --> 08:53.798
And those transformations
at the top look just beautiful.

08:53.832 --> 08:55.368
They just really look
beautiful.

08:55.400 --> 08:56.434
- Thank you.

08:56.469 --> 08:57.570
- And they really follow
the idea

08:57.602 --> 09:00.038
and you just have
so much charm.

09:00.072 --> 09:03.609
And then the thing at the end
was really great.

09:03.643 --> 09:07.178
And I know you'd like to know
whether you fooled us or not.

09:07.212 --> 09:10.081
And so would we.

09:10.115 --> 09:12.985
This was right--it's
a really tough call for us.

09:13.019 --> 09:15.520
We are going to go
to the judges

09:15.554 --> 09:18.857
and they're going to decide
whether we were fooled or not,

09:18.890 --> 09:21.126
and whatever they say
goes for us.

09:21.159 --> 09:24.263
So Alyson, it's to you.

09:24.297 --> 09:26.599
- All right, I'm talking
to the judges.

09:26.631 --> 09:31.636
They said this was really
tough decision for them too.

09:31.671 --> 09:35.908
But at the end of the day,
you did not fool them.

09:35.942 --> 09:38.177
- It was so good.
[applause]

09:38.210 --> 09:40.712
- But it was close.
- Thank you for having me.

09:40.745 --> 09:42.782
- You didn't fool 'em,
but it was amazing.

09:42.815 --> 09:44.817
- Bye.
- Mellow.

09:44.850 --> 09:46.719
- Thank you for having me.
[cheers and applause]

09:46.751 --> 09:48.453
- Bye.
- Bye.

09:48.486 --> 09:50.889
[applause]

09:50.923 --> 09:52.991
- Before Penn and Teller
can perform

09:53.024 --> 09:54.927
one of their signature tricks,

09:54.961 --> 09:57.996
they have to try and bust
another magician or two

09:58.029 --> 09:59.432
right after the break.

09:59.465 --> 10:01.933
[cheers and applause]

10:09.508 --> 10:12.345
[cheers and applause]

10:12.378 --> 10:14.980
- Welcome back.
Thirsty for more magic?

10:15.014 --> 10:17.984
Well, drink in
this next performance.

10:20.318 --> 10:22.421
- Kids really need
parental support.

10:22.455 --> 10:23.755
My parents weren't there
for me,

10:23.788 --> 10:26.558
but I was so lucky
I had my grandmother.

10:26.591 --> 10:28.727
She helped me pursue magic
in so many ways.

10:28.760 --> 10:31.297
She printed my business cards,
paid for merchandise,

10:31.330 --> 10:33.164
and even booked me
my first gig.

10:33.198 --> 10:34.834
I came from a very small town.

10:34.866 --> 10:36.769
It was 30 minutes
to get anywhere,

10:36.802 --> 10:39.270
and there was
absolute nothing.

10:39.304 --> 10:41.173
So when I first came to Vegas,

10:41.206 --> 10:43.842
my mind was blown
by the grand theatrics

10:43.875 --> 10:46.711
and the crazy production value
of the magic there.

10:46.745 --> 10:48.947
[upbeat music]

10:48.980 --> 10:52.217
When a female tells people
they do magic,

10:52.250 --> 10:54.120
too often I'm asked,

10:54.153 --> 10:56.455
"Oh, who do you work with?
Who do you assist?"

10:56.489 --> 10:58.857
But obviously,
it's a dumb question

10:58.890 --> 11:01.226
because girls can do magic,
too.

11:01.259 --> 11:03.495
I am truly obsessed
with sports.

11:03.528 --> 11:06.899
My most relaxing thing to do
is go to a baseball game

11:06.932 --> 11:08.634
and pick up a deck of cards.

11:08.668 --> 11:10.436
To calm down
before my stage shows,

11:10.469 --> 11:12.171
I even watch a game
on my phone.

11:12.203 --> 11:14.639
So hopefully tonight,
I can throw Penn and Teller

11:14.673 --> 11:18.210
a curve ball
and score myself a trophy.

11:19.611 --> 11:23.149
[cheers and applause]

11:23.182 --> 11:27.653
- Get ready for some twisted
magic from Paige Thompson.

11:27.687 --> 11:28.888
[cheers and applause]

11:28.921 --> 11:31.923
- Hello. I need to begin
by telling you both that

11:31.956 --> 11:34.059
when you're a female
and into magic,

11:34.092 --> 11:35.894
a lot of people assume

11:35.927 --> 11:37.429
you're a witch.
[laughter]

11:37.462 --> 11:39.298
Now, the upside to this

11:39.331 --> 11:42.268
is you get some
pretty nifty witchy gifts.

11:42.301 --> 11:44.336
A lot like this pentagram.

11:44.370 --> 11:46.105
Yes, I know
what you're thinking

11:46.138 --> 11:47.807
and you are completely wrong.

11:47.840 --> 11:49.475
Hollywood and serial killers

11:49.508 --> 11:51.342
have really given these
a bad rep.

11:51.376 --> 11:55.246
They're actually intended
for your protection,

11:55.280 --> 11:59.118
especially this one,
because we have here

11:59.150 --> 12:03.121
a Penntagram.
[laughter]

12:03.154 --> 12:05.323
Yes.
And we're going to use this

12:05.356 --> 12:08.626
to test the powers
of this Penntagram

12:08.660 --> 12:12.831
to save me from a very slow
and agonizing death

12:12.865 --> 12:15.500
right here on this stage

12:15.533 --> 12:18.104
because I have brought
with me tonight

12:18.136 --> 12:21.440
a bottle of nitric acid,

12:21.474 --> 12:26.812
the key ingredient
of fertilizers and explosives.

12:26.846 --> 12:30.048
Now, you're going to know
something is truly dangerous

12:30.081 --> 12:33.485
if I'm foregoing fashion
for safety.

12:33.519 --> 12:37.789
Okay. Drinking just
a few ounces of this acid

12:37.822 --> 12:40.392
will cause you to vomit blood,

12:40.426 --> 12:43.696
which will slowly
close your throat

12:43.729 --> 12:46.698
until you suffocate and die.

12:46.731 --> 12:47.799
Super fun.

12:47.832 --> 12:50.668
I have also brought
with me water,

12:50.702 --> 12:54.807
a liquid that is
completely indistinguishable

12:54.840 --> 12:57.342
from the nitric acid.

12:57.375 --> 13:00.779
We all know water
helps plants grow,

13:00.812 --> 13:04.250
gives fishies a little place
to swim around

13:04.283 --> 13:06.785
and well, reproduce.
[laughter]

13:06.818 --> 13:11.289
A little nasty,
but it won't kill you.

13:11.322 --> 13:13.292
Okay, time now

13:13.325 --> 13:18.163
to test the powers of
this Penntagram

13:18.197 --> 13:19.498
to protect me

13:19.532 --> 13:23.235
because we have here
three glasses full of water

13:23.269 --> 13:26.004
and one full of danger.

13:26.038 --> 13:29.808
Now, not much of a test if we
all know where the acid is.

13:29.841 --> 13:35.313
This is why I have brought
along my friend, lazy Susan.

13:35.346 --> 13:39.051
Now, Penn, I want to make this
as awkward as possible.

13:39.084 --> 13:44.056
Please gaze in to my eyes
as I spin and spin

13:44.088 --> 13:46.658
so nobody knows

13:46.692 --> 13:49.028
where the acid goes.

13:49.061 --> 13:52.230
Great. And Penn,
because you were so great,

13:52.264 --> 13:53.999
you're going to help me first.

13:54.033 --> 13:56.402
I need you to name two of these

13:56.434 --> 13:59.838
that you feel are safe
for me to drink.

13:59.871 --> 14:03.676
We have one, two, three, four.
Which two are safe?

14:03.708 --> 14:05.244
- Two and four.
- Two and four.

14:05.277 --> 14:10.014
You sounded confident,
but just out of pure curiosity,

14:10.048 --> 14:13.619
you really believe that
or are you guessing

14:13.652 --> 14:15.019
'cause you don't know me?

14:15.053 --> 14:16.855
So if I'm flopping around,
it's not a big deal.

14:16.889 --> 14:18.423
[laughter]

14:18.456 --> 14:19.591
- All of those.
- Great.

14:19.625 --> 14:21.192
- I'm guessing,
and I don't know you.

14:21.226 --> 14:22.995
[laughter]
- Honesty, the best.

14:23.028 --> 14:26.097
Oh, boy.
Well, here we go.

14:26.130 --> 14:28.100
[soft suspenseful music]

14:28.133 --> 14:30.134
♪ ♪

14:30.168 --> 14:32.370
Mm.
[applause]

14:32.403 --> 14:35.374
Refreshing. Okay.
Two was your other option.

14:35.407 --> 14:37.308
Do you want to change your mind
before I drink it?

14:37.342 --> 14:38.744
- Yes, I do.
- Oh, wow.

14:38.777 --> 14:40.980
- I wanna go to one.
- One.

14:41.013 --> 14:43.182
We're gonna swap-a-roo here.

14:43.215 --> 14:44.783
[inhales deeply]
Okay.

14:44.817 --> 14:46.317
♪ ♪

14:46.351 --> 14:47.485
Hoo.

14:47.519 --> 14:49.053
♪ ♪

14:49.087 --> 14:50.054
Okay.

14:50.088 --> 14:52.357
♪ ♪

14:52.390 --> 14:54.860
Mm-hmm.
[applause]

14:54.894 --> 14:56.495
Okay.

14:56.528 --> 14:59.431
So far, so good-ish.

14:59.465 --> 15:02.000
Terrified, but good-ish.

15:02.033 --> 15:04.302
Okay, Teller,
it is now your turn.

15:04.336 --> 15:08.640
Two remain.
One will kill me.

15:08.673 --> 15:10.142
The other,

15:10.174 --> 15:12.543
it's really going to make me
need to pee during

15:12.577 --> 15:14.312
my interview with Alyson.
[laughter]

15:14.346 --> 15:17.048
So tell her with my safety
your top priority,

15:17.081 --> 15:21.086
please tell me which one you
feel is safe for me to drink.

15:21.120 --> 15:22.354
We have one or two.

15:22.388 --> 15:24.789
Two?
That was very fast. This one.

15:24.822 --> 15:27.625
You are so positive.
You feel great.

15:27.659 --> 15:29.193
Okay.
You feel great.

15:29.227 --> 15:33.097
Well, I will thank you both now

15:33.131 --> 15:36.802
for letting me share
this bit of magic.

15:36.835 --> 15:39.203
Just in case
in a few short moments,

15:39.238 --> 15:41.974
my throat is
slowly closing shut.

15:42.006 --> 15:44.243
Okay.
[laughter]

15:44.275 --> 15:47.913
♪ ♪

15:47.947 --> 15:50.014
[audience exclaiming]

15:50.048 --> 15:51.450
Wrong pipe.
We're good--we're good.

15:51.482 --> 15:55.019
The acid remains. Great.
[applause]

15:55.053 --> 15:57.322
I know you don't look, like,
really impressed

15:57.355 --> 15:59.024
because
you're probably thinking,

15:59.057 --> 16:02.494
"Oh, she could have
filled those all with water."

16:02.528 --> 16:04.229
No. I am not here
to waste your time,

16:04.263 --> 16:07.633
which is why I brought along
some of my silverware

16:07.666 --> 16:11.403
because metal reacts crazily
with nitric acid.

16:11.437 --> 16:13.504
You see it
change color instantly,

16:13.538 --> 16:15.441
start to bubble ferociously.

16:15.474 --> 16:18.844
And not only that,
acid can actually eat

16:18.876 --> 16:20.946
through the lining
of your esophagus

16:20.980 --> 16:22.114
and through your teeth,

16:22.147 --> 16:25.951
but also right through
stainless steel

16:25.985 --> 16:28.120
just like that.
[applause]

16:28.153 --> 16:31.056
Whoo! My name is Paige Thompson
and I'm alive!

16:31.090 --> 16:32.591
[laughs]
[applause]

16:32.624 --> 16:35.661
- Paige Thompson!
Wow.

16:35.693 --> 16:38.629
Do you always incorporate like,
you know,

16:38.663 --> 16:40.899
things that could kill you
into your magic?

16:40.932 --> 16:42.500
- I've actually found
it's kind of fun,

16:42.533 --> 16:44.168
you know,
with the dangerous liquids,

16:44.202 --> 16:46.270
you hang upside down,
the straitjackets with fire,

16:46.304 --> 16:48.440
you know, all that
sort of shenanigans.

16:48.474 --> 16:50.808
- Right. Uh-huh.
Yeah, I mean as one does.

16:50.842 --> 16:52.177
[laughter]

16:52.211 --> 16:55.179
So how do you prepare for
a big performance like this?

16:55.213 --> 16:57.915
- Focus but not over-rehearse.

16:57.950 --> 17:01.386
And then do something I enjoy
like watch baseball

17:01.419 --> 17:03.755
or basketball or hockey or--

17:03.788 --> 17:05.023
- All right.

17:05.057 --> 17:06.759
Do you ever incorporate sports
into your act?

17:06.791 --> 17:09.827
- Oh, yes. I have a full
baseball-themed routine.

17:09.862 --> 17:11.462
- Do you?
- Yes.

17:11.497 --> 17:13.898
- Have all the men in magic
welcomed you in?

17:13.932 --> 17:15.534
- I didn't realize
when I was younger

17:15.567 --> 17:18.069
there wasn't females in magic.

17:18.103 --> 17:19.938
All my friends were guys

17:19.971 --> 17:22.407
and they didn't act like
I was a different magician.

17:22.441 --> 17:23.642
They just acted like,

17:23.674 --> 17:25.076
"Oh, here's our friend, Paige,
who does magic."

17:25.109 --> 17:26.744
And so I never felt excluded,

17:26.778 --> 17:28.480
which I think has
helped me a lot

17:28.513 --> 17:29.781
because I've always felt like

17:29.815 --> 17:31.650
I've had the support
of my friends.

17:31.682 --> 17:32.884
- Yeah.
All right, Paige.

17:32.917 --> 17:34.886
Let's see if you earned
yourself a trophy.

17:34.920 --> 17:36.288
- Okay.

17:36.320 --> 17:38.123
- Hello, Paige.
- Hello.

17:38.156 --> 17:40.025
- Boy, we're worried about you
for a while,

17:40.058 --> 17:42.193
but then at the end,
you came through.

17:42.227 --> 17:44.663
Plop, plop, fizz, fizz,
what a relief it is, huh?

17:44.695 --> 17:46.365
That you
came through like that.

17:46.397 --> 17:48.000
You came through fine.
That was great.

17:48.032 --> 17:51.103
You know,
we do the roulette thing.

17:51.135 --> 17:52.805
- Yeah.
- It's a common theme in magic.

17:52.837 --> 17:55.773
We did rodent roulette
on "Letterman" with rat traps.

17:55.807 --> 17:56.875
- Yes.

17:56.909 --> 17:58.143
- But you did
the most important thing

17:58.176 --> 18:01.180
with danger magic,
which is keeping it safe.

18:01.212 --> 18:03.382
You know, we don't allow
anybody on the show

18:03.414 --> 18:04.715
that's actually doing something

18:04.750 --> 18:06.617
that would actually
put someone in jeopardy.

18:06.652 --> 18:10.021
And you had that line between
playing with the danger,

18:10.055 --> 18:13.592
but also letting us know
that it was all in good fun.

18:13.625 --> 18:15.760
You also did one of the really
great things in magic,

18:15.794 --> 18:20.265
which is using a prop
that is used for one purpose

18:20.298 --> 18:21.532
in another purpose, you know,

18:21.567 --> 18:23.801
and it was
a very good use of that.

18:23.836 --> 18:26.105
I also loved the Penntagram

18:26.137 --> 18:28.240
and I think I'm going
to start marketing those.

18:28.272 --> 18:30.675
Teller's drawn
an envelope on a string

18:30.709 --> 18:34.579
and said, "it's a Tell-a-gram."
[laughter]

18:34.613 --> 18:36.280
You liked that joke
more than I did.

18:36.315 --> 18:38.750
Good. Very good.
- I liked that.

18:38.784 --> 18:41.220
- But it was a great routine.

18:41.252 --> 18:45.723
We love seeing women in magic
and we loved the routine.

18:45.757 --> 18:46.959
Very funny.
Very good.

18:46.991 --> 18:49.327
And we don't think
you've fooled us.

18:49.361 --> 18:51.896
- No, I don't think so.
- [laughing] Okay.

18:51.930 --> 18:54.098
- So you're convinced
they weren't fooled.

18:54.133 --> 18:56.768
- Oh, yes, no.
- Well, thank you so much.

18:56.801 --> 18:58.569
Paige Thompson.
[cheers and applause]

18:58.604 --> 19:00.838
- Thank you.
Thank you so much.

19:00.873 --> 19:03.808
[cheers and applause]

19:03.842 --> 19:07.078
- Something impossible awaits
you right after this.

19:07.112 --> 19:08.446
Stick around.

19:08.480 --> 19:10.915
[cheers and applause]

19:18.757 --> 19:21.093
[cheers and applause]

19:21.125 --> 19:22.426
- Welcome back.

19:22.461 --> 19:25.364
Let's meet out next
flinger-flickin' Fooler.

19:27.665 --> 19:30.568
- My name is Stanley Zhou.
I'm 16 years old.

19:30.602 --> 19:32.904
I grew up in China,
but four years ago,

19:32.938 --> 19:36.575
my mom brought me and my
brother from China to the U.S.

19:36.607 --> 19:38.777
I was always
very shy and awkward.

19:38.809 --> 19:41.279
And now on top of that,
I didn't speak any English,

19:41.313 --> 19:42.914
so I couldn't talk to anyone.

19:42.948 --> 19:47.118
So I taught myself English
with thousands of index cards.

19:47.152 --> 19:50.189
In some ways,
that was my first card trick.

19:50.221 --> 19:54.292
Eventually, I discovered magic
and it became my super power

19:54.326 --> 19:57.296
because now I can suddenly
connect with people

19:57.328 --> 20:00.432
and make friends
without any language barriers.

20:00.464 --> 20:02.166
I'll admit it,
I'm very ambitious.

20:02.201 --> 20:06.137
My two biggest passions
are fencing and magic.

20:06.171 --> 20:07.605
When I started fencing,

20:07.638 --> 20:11.643
I always wanted to go to the
nationals, which I have.

20:11.676 --> 20:16.381
And when I started doing magic,
I practice every day for hours.

20:16.414 --> 20:18.951
And now three years later,
I'm on "Fool Us."

20:18.983 --> 20:20.419
Penn, Teller,

20:20.451 --> 20:23.221
you guys have been doing magic
a lot longer than I have,

20:23.255 --> 20:26.157
so I'll find another way
to fool you.

20:27.159 --> 20:30.194
[cheers and applause]

20:30.962 --> 20:32.230
- Put your hands together

20:32.263 --> 20:36.701
for a 16-year-old magician,
Stanley Zhou.

20:36.734 --> 20:38.369
[cheers and applause]

20:38.403 --> 20:40.439
- Hi, Penn. Hi, Teller.
- Hey, Stanley.

20:40.471 --> 20:42.207
I can't believe
I'm sitting here in front of

20:42.240 --> 20:43.741
two of the greatest minds
in magic.

20:43.775 --> 20:45.277
- Oh, thank you.

20:45.309 --> 20:47.211
- It'd be crazy for me to try
to fool you with a card trick.

20:47.246 --> 20:49.181
So I won't. Instead,

20:49.213 --> 20:52.750
I'm going to try and fool you
with a physics experiment.

20:52.784 --> 20:55.953
Now, this physics experiment
requires three red cards

20:55.988 --> 20:57.122
and three black cards.

20:57.154 --> 20:59.557
You two will be
our independent observers

20:59.590 --> 21:01.292
to validate the results.

21:01.326 --> 21:03.362
I want you to notice
that the rest of the deck

21:03.394 --> 21:04.363
is well-mixed.

21:04.395 --> 21:07.665
Yes?
- Yes.

21:07.699 --> 21:09.166
- Perfect.

21:09.201 --> 21:11.803
This deck will be
our scientific control group.

21:11.836 --> 21:14.905
I'll set it aside for now
and I won't touch it.

21:14.940 --> 21:17.976
Now, my research has shown
that black ink weighs

21:18.009 --> 21:19.711
more than red ink.

21:19.744 --> 21:22.146
To demonstrate this,
I'll separate the cards,

21:22.180 --> 21:23.848
three blacks, three reds.

21:23.882 --> 21:25.784
And I'll mix them up
alternating.

21:25.817 --> 21:29.921
Black, red,
black, red, black, red.

21:29.954 --> 21:31.957
If I pick them up
and drop them,

21:31.990 --> 21:34.492
the heavier black ink
will cause the black cards

21:34.526 --> 21:35.861
to pass through the red cards.

21:35.894 --> 21:37.561
And then they end up
on the bottom.

21:37.596 --> 21:42.534
Let me show you.
There.

21:42.567 --> 21:44.236
I think that did it.

21:44.269 --> 21:45.936
If we take a look now,

21:45.971 --> 21:50.208
the first card,
that's a red card.

21:50.241 --> 21:51.977
The second card,
it used to be a black card,

21:52.009 --> 21:56.548
but since we dropped them,
it's also a red card.

21:56.580 --> 22:00.152
And the third card,
another red card.

22:00.184 --> 22:01.420
Thank you.
[applause]

22:01.452 --> 22:03.989
And if you're wondering,
over here

22:04.021 --> 22:07.992
are the three black cards.
[applause]

22:08.026 --> 22:10.295
Thank you.
Now, I don't know about you,

22:10.328 --> 22:12.263
but that seemed
pretty fair to me.

22:12.297 --> 22:15.299
However, I still sense
some skepticism,

22:15.334 --> 22:19.104
which is fine because science,
like magic, needs skeptics.

22:19.136 --> 22:21.105
So I'll demonstrate this again.

22:21.138 --> 22:24.442
And this time you'll know
exactly what to look for.

22:24.476 --> 22:26.510
Penn, what color
are these cards?

22:26.545 --> 22:28.180
- Black.
- Exactly.

22:28.212 --> 22:31.349
So that means that Teller
must have the three red cards.

22:31.383 --> 22:35.186
If you don't trust me, you can
check again to make sure.

22:35.220 --> 22:37.823
He doesn't trust me.
[laughter]

22:37.855 --> 22:40.424
Here, help me mix the red cards
into black cards,

22:40.459 --> 22:42.326
just like this.

22:42.361 --> 22:44.962
First one.

22:44.996 --> 22:48.266
Good.

22:48.299 --> 22:51.103
And perfect.

22:51.135 --> 22:54.772
Now, once again,
we're going to drop the cards

22:54.806 --> 22:58.509
and the black cards are going
to pass through the red cards.

22:58.542 --> 23:00.545
I saw it.
Did you see it? Penn? Teller?

23:00.578 --> 23:02.213
- I didn't.
- You didn't?

23:02.247 --> 23:03.214
- I didn't
- Come on.

23:03.248 --> 23:04.482
You're my independent observer.

23:04.516 --> 23:06.250
- I didn't see them
actually move.

23:06.284 --> 23:07.519
It just looked like
you dropped them.

23:07.551 --> 23:10.654
- Well, who knows?
Maybe it worked.

23:10.689 --> 23:12.457
Let's check it out.

23:12.490 --> 23:17.261
First card is red.

23:17.295 --> 23:19.998
Red.

23:20.030 --> 23:22.601
And red. Thank you.
[applause]

23:22.634 --> 23:26.505
And over here.

23:26.538 --> 23:28.240
Thank you.
[applause]

23:28.272 --> 23:30.040
- Very nice.

23:30.075 --> 23:33.177
- I'll admit that
while this experiment

23:33.211 --> 23:36.781
appears to have been perfectly
and scientifically fair,

23:36.815 --> 23:39.651
I did handle the cards
after Teller mixed them.

23:39.683 --> 23:43.721
And as a magician physicist
with incredibly fast fingers...

23:43.755 --> 23:45.990
[laughter]
I might've done something.

23:46.023 --> 23:49.059
I might have used
sleight of hand. Who knows?

23:49.094 --> 23:51.229
So for those of you
who still may be thinking

23:51.262 --> 23:54.332
that this is a card trick
and not a physics experiment

23:54.365 --> 23:56.167
and to put all doubt to rest,

23:56.201 --> 23:59.837
I'm going to create a condition
that only physics can solve.

23:59.871 --> 24:03.040
I have invented a sleight
of hand prevention machine.

24:03.074 --> 24:06.344
The first part
is this hole punch.

24:06.377 --> 24:08.446
Penn, you can check that out.

24:08.480 --> 24:11.615
And the second part
is the paper fastener.

24:11.650 --> 24:12.750
- Okay.

24:12.784 --> 24:14.920
- Teller,
you can take a look at that.

24:14.952 --> 24:17.689
Now to prevent sleight of hand,
we just punch a hole

24:17.721 --> 24:20.325
in each one of my fingers.
[laughter]

24:20.357 --> 24:21.893
Just kidding.

24:21.926 --> 24:25.196
What we're actually going to do
is punch a hole in the cards.

24:25.230 --> 24:26.998
There we go. That's good.

24:27.031 --> 24:30.602
And we're going to use
that paper fastener. Thank you,

24:30.634 --> 24:33.771
To make sure that
I can't use sleight of hand

24:33.805 --> 24:37.442
to make the cards move,
just like this.

24:37.476 --> 24:39.243
Now, if you take a look,
the cards are really

24:39.277 --> 24:42.314
alternating red, black,
red, black, red, black.

24:42.346 --> 24:43.647
And you can see
that there's no way

24:43.682 --> 24:45.115
we can change
the order of the cards

24:45.150 --> 24:47.251
no matter
which way we turned them.

24:47.285 --> 24:50.087
And if you think about it,
if this were a card trick,

24:50.121 --> 24:52.723
the paper fastener
will make it impossible.

24:52.757 --> 24:56.528
But this isn't a card trick,
it's a physics experiment.

24:56.560 --> 24:59.663
♪ ♪

24:59.698 --> 25:01.199
I think that did it.

25:01.232 --> 25:03.201
♪ ♪

25:03.234 --> 25:07.071
Look.
That's red...

25:07.105 --> 25:10.075
red, and red.
[audience exclaims]

25:10.107 --> 25:15.212
And black, black, and black.
[applause]

25:15.247 --> 25:17.816
But that's not all.

25:17.848 --> 25:19.116
You see,

25:19.150 --> 25:22.787
the real physical evidence
is in our control group.

25:22.820 --> 25:24.588
The stack of cards.

25:24.623 --> 25:26.490
Remember,
it was totally mixed up

25:26.525 --> 25:29.728
before I set it down
and hasn't been touched since.

25:29.760 --> 25:34.365
If black ink truly is heavier
than red, this shall prove it.

25:34.398 --> 25:36.835
♪ ♪

25:36.867 --> 25:39.538
And if you take a look,

25:39.570 --> 25:42.339
you'll see that all the red
cards have come to the top

25:42.374 --> 25:45.009
and all the black cards
to the bottom.

25:45.042 --> 25:47.811
Thank you very much.
[cheers and applause]

25:47.846 --> 25:49.180
Thank you, Penn.
Thank you, Teller.

25:49.213 --> 25:53.084
- Can we take these with us?
- Sure, go ahead.

25:53.117 --> 25:56.253
- Stanley Zhou. Hi.
- Hi.

25:56.288 --> 25:58.957
- So nice to meet you.
- Nice to meet you.

25:58.990 --> 26:01.559
- You're so incredible.
- Thank you so much.

26:01.593 --> 26:03.361
- How long have you been
doing this?

26:03.394 --> 26:04.729
- Doing magic?
- Yeah.

26:04.762 --> 26:06.196
- Only about three years.

26:06.230 --> 26:07.432
- Wow.
- Yeah.

26:07.464 --> 26:10.000
- Three years and you're
already here at "Fool Us"

26:10.035 --> 26:12.403
doing close-up magic
with Penn and Teller.

26:12.436 --> 26:13.571
- Yes.

26:13.605 --> 26:15.006
- And is your family
supportive?

26:15.039 --> 26:16.106
- Yes, of course.
- Yeah.

26:16.141 --> 26:17.675
- I wouldn't be here
without them.

26:17.709 --> 26:19.109
- [chuckling]
That's true.

26:19.144 --> 26:22.047
It's so brave to do these
tricks with Penn and Teller

26:22.079 --> 26:24.048
sitting right in front of you.
[chuckles]

26:24.082 --> 26:26.250
- Well, of course,
I was nervous at first,

26:26.284 --> 26:29.721
but once I got out,
I just kinda got into the zone.

26:29.753 --> 26:32.824
- And so are you actually good
at physics as well?

26:32.856 --> 26:33.959
- Yeah.

26:33.991 --> 26:35.693
- I feel like you're good
at everything.

26:35.727 --> 26:36.927
It's just a hunch.

26:36.961 --> 26:38.496
- I don't know, actually.
- [laughs]

26:38.529 --> 26:41.132
What other goals do you have
for yourself?

26:41.165 --> 26:43.667
- I really,
really enjoy fencing.

26:43.701 --> 26:46.104
- Ooh.
- It's just a really cool

26:46.136 --> 26:49.173
combination of mental
and physical skills.

26:49.207 --> 26:50.642
- All right, Stanley.

26:50.674 --> 26:52.576
Let's see if Penn and Teller
know how you did your trick.

26:52.611 --> 26:55.346
- All right.

26:55.380 --> 26:56.914
- Stanley.

26:56.948 --> 26:57.949
- [chuckles]
- Yes.

26:57.982 --> 27:00.085
- I want to apologize to you

27:00.117 --> 27:03.288
'cause I think I cheated
a little bit on the game.

27:03.320 --> 27:04.722
I asked you at the end,

27:04.756 --> 27:07.925
if I could take this prop
with me

27:07.959 --> 27:10.394
and I'm really not
supposed to do that.

27:10.428 --> 27:13.798
I mean, during this section,
I can ask about props,

27:13.832 --> 27:16.667
but I'm not supposed to
within the performance,

27:16.701 --> 27:19.104
ask to grab something
you didn't offer to me.

27:19.136 --> 27:22.740
And when I did it,
my heart kind of sunk

27:22.773 --> 27:25.509
because I said, here's
this guy, he 16-years-old.

27:25.542 --> 27:27.345
You've been in the country.
What? Three years?

27:27.378 --> 27:28.747
- Three, four years.

27:28.779 --> 27:30.914
- Four years.
Been in the country four years,

27:30.949 --> 27:32.750
learning English,
learning magic.

27:32.784 --> 27:36.287
I'm here on our show

27:36.320 --> 27:38.890
and it was kind
of a [bleep] move...

27:38.923 --> 27:40.191
[laughter]

27:40.224 --> 27:42.426
To say, "Can I take this?"
and put you on the spot.

27:42.460 --> 27:45.096
You don't have a choice.
You can't say no,

27:45.130 --> 27:47.265
because that shows
how the trick is done.

27:47.298 --> 27:49.433
So you have to say yes,
then we take it away.

27:49.467 --> 27:53.438
And we bust the trick.
So I--I--I apologize.

27:53.471 --> 27:55.973
I don't feel like
this is good or righteous

27:56.007 --> 27:57.075
or I did the right thing.

27:57.107 --> 28:00.979
I feel like I cheated
on the game

28:01.011 --> 28:03.213
and then I looked at this prop
and...

28:03.248 --> 28:04.582
- Yeah.

28:07.919 --> 28:09.386
- [snorting chuckle]
- You fooled us.

28:09.421 --> 28:12.123
- [gasps] You did it!
[cheers and applause]

28:12.156 --> 28:15.226
- Thank you.
- Yay! Congratulations!

28:15.259 --> 28:17.961
- I'm kind of exonerated
from my cheating

28:17.996 --> 28:20.898
because you fooled us anyway.
[cheers and applause]

28:20.932 --> 28:25.903
- Thank you so much.
Thank you, Penn.

28:25.936 --> 28:28.472
Thank you, Teller.
- I shouldn't have done that.

28:28.506 --> 28:29.574
- Thank you.

28:29.606 --> 28:31.041
- I shouldn't have done that
but--

28:31.076 --> 28:33.411
- Stanley Zhou!
- Thank you.

28:33.444 --> 28:36.047
[cheers and applause]

28:36.080 --> 28:37.781
- [chuckles]

28:37.816 --> 28:41.486
There goes one fine Fooler
with a "Fool Us" trophy.

28:41.519 --> 28:44.189
Can another magician fool
our boys tonight?

28:44.221 --> 28:46.090
Come back and find out.

28:46.124 --> 28:48.625
[cheers and applause]

28:56.067 --> 28:59.269
[cheers and applause]

28:59.304 --> 29:00.672
- Welcome back.

29:00.704 --> 29:03.674
Penn and Teller gave up
one "Fool Us" trophy so far.

29:03.708 --> 29:06.510
They might give away another
to our next act.

29:06.544 --> 29:08.011
Let's meet them.

29:10.347 --> 29:12.317
- I'm a Michigan magician.

29:12.349 --> 29:14.018
Try to say
that five times fast.

29:14.051 --> 29:15.385
I met my girlfriend, Jasmine,

29:15.420 --> 29:16.954
at a magic convention
in Michigan

29:16.988 --> 29:18.722
called the
"Abbott's Magic Get Together"

29:18.757 --> 29:20.157
where we were both performing.

29:20.191 --> 29:21.492
She really put a spell on me.

29:21.526 --> 29:23.127
Fast forward a year,

29:23.161 --> 29:25.329
and we have a little girl
named Paizley Abbott.

29:25.363 --> 29:27.898
And that's so we remember
where she sprang from.

29:27.932 --> 29:29.433
We do a lot of county fairs,

29:29.467 --> 29:32.302
traveling around Michigan
and the Midwest.

29:32.336 --> 29:35.839
I have a 30-foot trailer
with a built-in stage

29:35.874 --> 29:38.542
and my very own
animatronic chicken.

29:38.576 --> 29:39.877
[laughter]

29:39.911 --> 29:42.212
People ask me if I ever want
to open a show in Vegas.

29:42.247 --> 29:45.115
And I tell them, no, I'll
do it right here in Michigan,

29:45.150 --> 29:46.917
'cause that's my home.

29:46.951 --> 29:48.752
Tonight, I'll be
bringing out a trick

29:48.787 --> 29:51.221
that's taken me five years
to perfect.

29:51.256 --> 29:52.656
Since Battle Creek, Michigan

29:52.690 --> 29:54.392
is the cereal center
of the world,

29:54.424 --> 29:57.261
it takes a Michigan magician
to pull it off.

29:57.295 --> 30:01.833
Penn, Teller, prepare for the
breakfast of magical champions.

30:02.733 --> 30:05.502
[cheers and applause]

30:05.537 --> 30:09.941
- Give it up for Michigan's own
Jonathan Lachance.

30:09.973 --> 30:11.509
[cheers and applause]

30:11.542 --> 30:12.977
- When I was a kid, to me,

30:13.010 --> 30:16.748
nothing said magic more
than a bowl in a box of cereal.

30:16.780 --> 30:19.450
And I'm not even talking
about the food.

30:19.483 --> 30:21.853
I mean, on the inside
of every single box,

30:21.885 --> 30:23.555
there was a prize
at the bottom,

30:23.587 --> 30:26.324
pour out some sugary,
over-processed grain,

30:26.356 --> 30:28.692
get a toy. Magic.
[audience murmurs]

30:28.726 --> 30:32.063
Yeah, I know this was just a
cheap hook to sell more cereal,

30:32.096 --> 30:34.531
but guess what?
It worked.

30:34.566 --> 30:37.669
Penn and Teller,
in front of you is an envelope.

30:37.701 --> 30:41.205
Would you please open it?

30:41.239 --> 30:42.707
Inside, you'll find a list

30:42.740 --> 30:47.045
containing the top 20 common
items found in cereal boxes,

30:47.077 --> 30:49.980
things like baseball cards,
snap bracelets,

30:50.013 --> 30:52.450
and my personal favorite,
the mini terrarium,

30:52.482 --> 30:54.853
because who doesn't like
a tiny garden of weeds

30:54.885 --> 30:57.288
as a side order for cereal?
[laughter]

30:57.322 --> 31:01.226
If you both could settle on
one prize you see on the list.

31:01.259 --> 31:03.560
- No, no, they don't do that.

31:03.595 --> 31:05.829
- Okay. We got one.
- All right. And what is it?

31:05.864 --> 31:07.097
- X-ray specs.

31:07.131 --> 31:09.166
- X-ray specs.
Excellent choice.

31:09.200 --> 31:10.734
- Thank you.
- Okay.

31:10.768 --> 31:13.171
So now that we have the prize,
it's time to select the cereal.

31:13.203 --> 31:15.006
And Alyson,
would you mind joining me

31:15.038 --> 31:16.273
at the breakfast table?

31:16.307 --> 31:17.674
- Gladly.

31:17.709 --> 31:21.378
- So I have a bag with six mini
cereal boxes in it.

31:21.412 --> 31:24.515
And can you verify
the bag is empty?

31:24.548 --> 31:25.817
- Yes.
- Awesome.

31:25.849 --> 31:28.318
And let's see
what choices we have.

31:28.353 --> 31:30.654
We have Huffle Puffs.
[laughter]

31:30.688 --> 31:34.726
Okay.
We have Malt-O Magic.

31:34.759 --> 31:38.730
And we have Presto Pops...
- Mm.

31:38.762 --> 31:41.732
- Mysteerios...
[laughter]

31:41.766 --> 31:44.501
Hocus Oatus...
[laughter]

31:44.535 --> 31:48.538
and lastly, Abra-cadapples.
[laughter]

31:48.573 --> 31:51.308
Okay. Alyson, if you could
please shake up the bags

31:51.342 --> 31:53.778
so we can make
a totally random selection.

31:53.810 --> 31:58.615
Okay, keep shaking it up.

31:58.650 --> 32:01.451
You good? Okay, great.
[laughter]

32:01.486 --> 32:03.621
Now that you've mixed up
our choices, let's pick one.

32:03.654 --> 32:07.458
Reach inside and grab one box.
And what do we have?

32:07.491 --> 32:09.760
- Yay, Presto Pops.
- Presto Pops.

32:09.794 --> 32:12.462
And here's what
we could have had.

32:12.497 --> 32:15.266
And Alyson, you want to know
something weird?

32:15.299 --> 32:17.268
I knew that you were
going to pick this cereal

32:17.301 --> 32:20.038
and that's because
it matches my prediction.

32:20.070 --> 32:21.873
- Oh.

32:21.905 --> 32:23.740
- It gets better. Watch.

32:23.775 --> 32:29.180
If we open up the box here
on the inside...

32:29.212 --> 32:30.315
Presto Pops.

32:30.347 --> 32:32.916
- Wow.
[applause]

32:32.951 --> 32:35.319
- Now--but there's more, okay?

32:35.353 --> 32:39.123
If we fold up the box here--

32:39.156 --> 32:41.092
and we have to use
a little magic for this,

32:41.125 --> 32:45.229
and I think you actually have
something we need right here.

32:45.262 --> 32:47.230
Just like that.
Hold on to that for me.

32:47.265 --> 32:50.000
And take the bowl
and hold it right there

32:50.034 --> 32:52.269
and wave the spoon
over the top of the box

32:52.302 --> 32:53.837
and say,
"sugar coma in a bowl."

32:53.871 --> 32:55.740
[laughter]
- Sugar coma in a bowl.

32:55.772 --> 32:57.307
- And watch this.
- Wow.

32:57.342 --> 32:59.277
- Just like that,
we have something

32:59.309 --> 33:01.179
inside--inside the box
right there,

33:01.211 --> 33:03.513
we have Presto Pops,
but there's actually a prize.

33:03.548 --> 33:05.349
Penn, what was the prize
you guys selected?

33:05.383 --> 33:06.616
- X-ray specs.

33:06.651 --> 33:07.684
- You had a free choice
out of 20.

33:07.719 --> 33:10.054
- We did.
- And what is in there?

33:10.087 --> 33:11.556
[audience exclaims]

33:11.588 --> 33:14.358
X-ray specs.
Now, here's the thing.

33:14.392 --> 33:16.693
We have 98% of the trick.

33:16.728 --> 33:19.063
We have the bowl,
we have the prize,

33:19.096 --> 33:21.398
we have the spoon,
and we have the cereal.

33:21.432 --> 33:23.835
The only thing we need now
is the--here.

33:23.867 --> 33:25.470
You know what?
Take a look inside the box.

33:25.502 --> 33:26.738
Do you see anything
at the bottom?

33:26.770 --> 33:28.506
- No.
- No?

33:28.538 --> 33:30.674
That's because--oh.

33:30.708 --> 33:32.977
Well, I guess there's one thing
that got past your eyes.

33:33.010 --> 33:34.746
And when, I mean,
past your eyes,

33:34.778 --> 33:38.048
I'm talking about the other 2%.
[audience exclaims]

33:38.082 --> 33:41.051
And that's a magical breakfast
of champions.

33:41.085 --> 33:44.255
[applause]
- Jonathan Lachance.

33:44.288 --> 33:46.790
[cheers and applause]
[indistinct chatter]

33:46.824 --> 33:50.627
So your mom never told you
to not play with your food?

33:50.661 --> 33:51.929
- No. Well, that was
the biggest thing.

33:51.962 --> 33:53.865
I used to take my grubby
little paws and stick them

33:53.897 --> 33:55.500
all the way at the bottom
searching for that toy.

33:55.532 --> 33:58.236
- Yes, or you could just
flip it open

33:58.269 --> 33:59.636
and open it from the bottom.

33:59.670 --> 34:00.904
- Yeah.
I never thought of that.

34:00.938 --> 34:05.175
- Right. So is this the trick
you're known for?

34:05.209 --> 34:06.576
- So this is actually a trick

34:06.611 --> 34:08.478
that I've been working on
for like five years and...

34:08.512 --> 34:09.947
- Wow.
- And kind of a trick

34:09.981 --> 34:11.681
I really wanted to do
on this show.

34:11.715 --> 34:14.117
- It's pretty awesome.
- Thank you.

34:14.152 --> 34:16.653
- Have you done lots
of virtual magic this year?

34:16.686 --> 34:17.789
- I did.

34:17.822 --> 34:19.590
I did a show for like
over 5,000 people

34:19.623 --> 34:20.757
all over the world.

34:20.791 --> 34:22.827
- So how else did you spend
your time?

34:22.860 --> 34:25.195
- I became a firefighter.

34:25.228 --> 34:26.364
- What!
- Yes.

34:26.396 --> 34:27.632
- That's amazing.

34:27.664 --> 34:28.833
- Yeah. I like to do stuff

34:28.865 --> 34:30.568
in the public
and help the public out.

34:30.601 --> 34:34.105
And with magic, I've done a lot
of, like, charity events

34:34.137 --> 34:36.574
and so it was just kind of
a give back thing

34:36.606 --> 34:37.942
that I wanted to do.

34:37.974 --> 34:39.976
- All right, Jonathan,
let's see if Penn and Teller

34:40.010 --> 34:42.012
can see through
your cereal trick.

34:42.045 --> 34:43.481
- Awesome.

34:43.514 --> 34:46.884
- Hey John, I'll tell you,
you've made "Fool Us" history.

34:46.918 --> 34:48.219
- Yeah?

34:48.251 --> 34:51.422
- We have not seen
a cereal magic routine before.

34:51.456 --> 34:52.856
- Awesome.
- You've got it.

34:52.889 --> 34:55.092
You own that whole area.
- Yeah.

34:55.126 --> 34:57.494
- That was really,
really nice and funny.

34:57.527 --> 35:01.398
And there's also, it's such
a magical premise, you know,

35:01.431 --> 35:04.802
to have a box of cereal,
you know,

35:04.835 --> 35:06.971
and have something
hidden in that box

35:07.003 --> 35:10.675
is just this magical idea
that you're going to find--

35:10.708 --> 35:12.610
you're going to find
the whole secret in the box

35:12.643 --> 35:13.811
when you pour the stuff out.

35:13.844 --> 35:15.880
Now, remember that
when I was a child,

35:15.913 --> 35:17.949
you know, I had this little--

35:17.981 --> 35:19.851
I had a little bag
that I carried to school.

35:19.884 --> 35:21.585
My mom would give me change
in the bag.

35:21.619 --> 35:22.719
I hid the change in the bag.

35:22.753 --> 35:24.155
I'd go to the store,
buy the cereal,

35:24.188 --> 35:26.224
then hidden in the box
was the whole secret.

35:26.257 --> 35:28.492
And I'd pull that out
and it was just great.

35:28.525 --> 35:30.327
And I don't think
you expected to fool us

35:30.360 --> 35:33.965
with how you poured the milk
out and the cereal out.

35:33.998 --> 35:35.465
We had a pretty
good idea on that.

35:35.500 --> 35:38.835
And I think that as you're
listening between the lines

35:38.869 --> 35:41.539
or underlining certain words
that I said,

35:41.572 --> 35:43.773
I think you have an idea
what I'm saying to you

35:43.807 --> 35:45.876
and I don't think
you fooled us.

35:45.909 --> 35:48.278
- I did not.
- Aw.

35:48.311 --> 35:50.081
Oh, well, Jonathan,
you didn't fool them,

35:50.114 --> 35:52.083
but we absolutely loved
that trick.

35:52.115 --> 35:53.985
Thank you so much.
- Thank you.

35:54.018 --> 35:58.054
- Jonathan Lachance.
[cheers and applause]

35:59.623 --> 36:01.759
Penn and Teller
have talked the talk.

36:01.791 --> 36:04.795
Now they get to walk the walk
with a trick of their own

36:04.829 --> 36:06.530
when "Fool Us" returns.

36:06.563 --> 36:07.965
[cheers and applause]

36:16.541 --> 36:18.943
[cheers and applause]

36:18.976 --> 36:22.547
- Joined by a randomly-selected
host of this show,

36:22.579 --> 36:25.849
give it up for our headliners,
Penn and Teller.

36:25.882 --> 36:28.485
[cheers and applause]

36:28.518 --> 36:30.487
- Alyson,
so many of these shows,

36:30.521 --> 36:32.056
we've done a trick for you
at the end.

36:32.088 --> 36:34.692
We think tonight,
you should do a trick for us,

36:34.724 --> 36:37.327
more specifically for Teller.

36:37.360 --> 36:38.329
You'll do all of this.

36:38.362 --> 36:39.764
I'll just kind of
talk you through.

36:39.797 --> 36:41.498
You've seen a lot
of magicians work.

36:41.532 --> 36:43.534
You know the basic idea,
just go through it.

36:43.568 --> 36:45.068
First, pull out
your deck of cards.

36:45.101 --> 36:47.804
Open them up.
- Oh, jeez.

36:47.838 --> 36:49.574
- Beautiful. Pull out
the cards, pull out the cards.

36:49.606 --> 36:51.041
You can throw the empty box
on the floor

36:51.074 --> 36:53.210
and get rid of--beautiful.
Now, give the cards a shuffle.

36:53.244 --> 36:54.911
Say, "Teller,
watch me shuffle."

36:54.945 --> 36:57.914
- Shuffle. I mean,
Teller, watch me shuffle.

36:57.949 --> 36:59.449
[laughter]
Not closely.

36:59.483 --> 37:00.717
- Do a legitimate shuffle.

37:00.751 --> 37:02.719
- I'm trying, but
it's a little intimidating.

37:02.753 --> 37:04.322
- Do a legitimate shuffle.
- You guys are really, like...

37:04.355 --> 37:05.690
- There you go.
Shuffle like a freak.

37:05.722 --> 37:07.023
- Really famous magicians.
- Shuffle like a freak.

37:07.057 --> 37:08.525
Beautiful, beautiful.

37:08.559 --> 37:10.094
Want to shuffle some more?
Shuffle some more.

37:10.126 --> 37:11.195
- My daughters always say

37:11.228 --> 37:12.762
I need
to practice shuffling more.

37:12.797 --> 37:14.197
- There you go.
- They're right.

37:14.231 --> 37:15.599
- Now, give 'em a cut,
give 'em a cut.

37:15.632 --> 37:17.969
- Okay. Okay. Okay.

37:18.001 --> 37:19.036
- And when you complete
the cut,

37:19.070 --> 37:20.036
now say, "Teller."

37:20.070 --> 37:21.405
- Teller!
- "Pick a card."

37:21.438 --> 37:22.606
What you are going to do
is spread them out like this.

37:22.639 --> 37:23.740
Turn them over like that.

37:23.773 --> 37:24.875
- Gosh.
- Spread them out just like

37:24.909 --> 37:26.978
that and say,
"pick any card you want."

37:27.010 --> 37:28.311
- Pick a card,
any card you want!

37:28.346 --> 37:30.047
- Get in your head. Okay.
He has got one.

37:30.081 --> 37:32.583
- He has got one.
- Now, gather them up like that

37:32.617 --> 37:34.485
and turn the deck over,
facedown,

37:34.518 --> 37:36.387
put it right down there
and say, "Teller."

37:36.420 --> 37:37.688
- Teller!

37:37.722 --> 37:38.822
- "You're going to
remember your card?"

37:38.856 --> 37:39.889
- You're going to remember
your card?

37:39.923 --> 37:41.659
- "Wait a minute, Teller."

37:41.692 --> 37:44.161
- Wait a minute, Teller.
- "You're a slimy weasel."

37:44.195 --> 37:47.231
- You're a slimy, cute weasel.
[laughter]

37:47.264 --> 37:49.065
- "Who has been riding
his whole career

37:49.099 --> 37:50.300
on the back of Penn."

37:50.333 --> 37:51.469
- [laughing]
Who's been--

37:51.501 --> 37:52.469
- You don't have to say that.
- Okay.

37:52.503 --> 37:54.038
- Just say,

37:54.070 --> 37:56.206
"But I think you might change
your mind just to screw me up."

37:56.239 --> 37:59.076
- I think you might change
your mind just to screw me up.

37:59.110 --> 38:01.445
- "So write down the name
of the card you picked."

38:01.478 --> 38:04.748
- So write down the name
of the card you picked.

38:04.782 --> 38:05.983
Oh, he--

38:06.016 --> 38:06.983
- "Just write it on your arm.
Who cares?"

38:07.018 --> 38:08.219
- On your arm.
Who cares?

38:08.251 --> 38:09.452
- "Write down the name
of the card you picked."

38:09.487 --> 38:12.088
- Write it down.
Don't let me see.

38:12.123 --> 38:14.057
- Don't--yeah, that's good.
That's a good ad-lib.

38:14.090 --> 38:15.525
- Okay, good.
- Really good.

38:15.559 --> 38:17.795
Now say, "I will find
your card, Teller."

38:17.827 --> 38:19.396
- I will find your card,
Teller.

38:19.429 --> 38:22.333
- Oh no, no. Watch this.
Show both hands empty.

38:22.365 --> 38:24.034
Show it to Teller.
You've seen all this.

38:24.068 --> 38:26.570
Now say,
"I'll cut right to your card."

38:26.603 --> 38:28.204
- I will cut
right to your card.

38:28.239 --> 38:29.239
- Now, listen carefully Alyson.

38:29.273 --> 38:31.242
Cut about a third
of the way down,

38:31.275 --> 38:33.443
then turn it over
and put the right back on top.

38:33.476 --> 38:35.146
- A third of the way down.
- Perfect.

38:35.179 --> 38:36.579
- Right here.
Oh, gosh.

38:36.614 --> 38:37.748
- Turn it over, turn it over.
- Turn it over.

38:37.782 --> 38:38.983
- And then, put it back
right on top.

38:39.016 --> 38:40.217
- And then--oh, right on top.
- Beautiful.

38:40.251 --> 38:42.152
And say," Five of hearts.
Is that your card?"

38:42.186 --> 38:44.355
- Five of hearts!
Is that your card?

38:44.387 --> 38:45.588
Oh, no.

38:45.623 --> 38:46.690
- Now, you gotta bail out
of it.

38:46.724 --> 38:48.793
You say,
"Of course it's not your card.

38:48.826 --> 38:50.393
- Of course,
It's not your card.

